					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">When you replace the belt, gear positions get moved and alignment gets out of whack. I think here is where it goes wrong for most people; there's a lot more involved in drive repair than just replacing the belt. <a href="http://www.famicomworld.com/forum/index.php?topic=10767.msg150064#msg150064" class="postlink">Here</a> is the most thorough guide I've seen.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">DrWho198 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Well, that does make some sense.<br />If I'm not mistaking (I'm new to the fds world) then hacker included a tool in they're backup software to align the header. How effective is this or is there a better way?<br />Because given the information that was discussed so far, there is no reason why a correctly aligned drive with a new belt wouldn't read/write perfectly. The only problem could occur when the drive was moved rufly or the belt stretched to the extent that it slips.</div><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.famicomdisksystem.com/disk-copy/">http://www.famicomdisksystem.com/disk-copy/</a><!-- m --><br />This talks about adjusting the drive speed, I don't think it helps with head alignment.<br />I have a debug version of my fdsstick software that does extra analysis for head adjustment, though I've never released it to the public.<br /><br /><img src="http://3dscapture.com/junk/fdsstick3.png" alt="Image" /></div>

					
